<subSubSection lastPageId="66" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,1326,2035]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1434,1459]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Description.</emphasis>
Possible 
<typeStatus box="[452,539,1435,1459]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">syntype</typeStatus>
specimens well preserved with body wall and chaetae largely intact, consists of four posteriorly incomplete specimens and several headless fragments. Alcohol-preserved animals yellowishbrown in colour, 
<quantity box="[342,435,1506,1531]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="2.0">2–7 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[506,641,1506,1531]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" unit="mm" value="0.44999999999999996" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.2">0.2–0.7 mm</quantity>
wide excluding buccal tentacles, 10–21 segments. Sex unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,1326,2035]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Dorsum anteriorly tessellated. Venter anteriorly with mid-ventral groove and discrete ventro-lateral pads; pads tessellated, extending to segment 12. Mid-ventral groove from segment 3.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,1326,2035]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
Buccal tentacles numerous, of 
<specimenCount box="[573,692,1615,1639]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
: (1) cylindrical, thickened distally, distinctly grooved and (2) cylindrical, uniformly thin, weakly grooved, both arising at junction between prostomium and upper lip. Prostomial ridge distinctly curved, extending laterally along anterodorsal base of upper lip. Upper lip prominent medial lobe and small wing-like lateral lobes, margin of medial lobe straight. Inner lower lip hidden by upper lip; outer region flat, shield-like, subtriangular and pointing toward mouth, extending posteriorly to segment 3. Achaetous segments visible dorsally but obscured by expanded outer lower lip ventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1437,1326,2035]" lastBlockId="66.[151,1440,151,608]" lastPageId="66" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
Notochaetigerous segments 25, extending to segment 27 (minimum); posteriorly incomplete. Notopodia digitiform, decreasing in size posteriorly, prechaetal lobe low, postchaetal lobe digitiform, postchaetal lobe equal long to prechaetal or slightly longer than prechaetal. Notochaetae within a chaetiger consisting of 
<specimenCount box="[1334,1436,1903,1927]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="generic" typeStatus="type">one type</specimenCount>
(chaetigers 4, 16, 25 examined), gradually elongating from dorsal to ventral, hirsute, uniformly tapered, posteriorly same form as those anteriorly, although fewer (
<figureCitation box="[676,771,1974,1999]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="66.[151,250,1869,1891]" captionTargetBox="[510,1074,671,1833]" captionTargetId="figure-256@66.[502,1084,663,1843]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURE 34. Polycirrus luminosus Verrill. a–c. Non type specimen YPM 1311a. Notochaeta illustrated at x40 and x100 from notopodium, chaetiger 25. b. Frontal view of uncinus from chaetiger 16. c. Lateral view of uncinus from chaetiger 25." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948478" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948478/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 34a</figureCitation>
). Neurochaetae beginning on segment 10 and present on all remaining segments (but all material is incomplete). Neuropodial tori ridge-like, similar along body. Uncini with short neck and straight to convex base (
<typeStatus box="[628,686,151,176]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Type</typeStatus>
1), teeth above main fang arranged in double transverse series (MF:1:10) enlarged median tooth above main fang present, subrostral process present as low, angular protuberance (
<figureCitation box="[159,283,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="66.[151,250,1869,1891]" captionTargetBox="[510,1074,671,1833]" captionTargetId="figure-256@66.[502,1084,663,1843]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURE 34. Polycirrus luminosus Verrill. a–c. Non type specimen YPM 1311a. Notochaeta illustrated at x40 and x100 from notopodium, chaetiger 25. b. Frontal view of uncinus from chaetiger 16. c. Lateral view of uncinus from chaetiger 25." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948478" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948478/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 34b, c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1440,151,608]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Nephridial papillae present, globular. Pre-gular membrane nephridial papillae absent. Post-gular membrane nephridial papillae present, extending from segment 5 to 11; situated at ventral base of notopodia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1440,151,608]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,332,357]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Comments.</emphasis>
Although the material examined is not labelled as 
<typeStatus box="[919,981,332,356]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">types</typeStatus>
, it matches well with the description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill, A. E." box="[151,305,367,392]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="595 - 671" refId="ref63662" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1900) Additions to the Turbellaria, Nemertina and Annelida of the Bermudas, with revisions of some New England genera and species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 10, 595 - 671., pl. 70." type="journal article" year="1900">Verrill (1900)</bibRefCitation>
and is from the same locality, Bailey Bay, 
<collectingCountry box="[790,896,367,392]" name="Bermuda" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
. We agree with 
<bibRefCitation author="Londono-Mesa, M." box="[1078,1331,367,392]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1 - 93" refId="ref62299" refString="Londono-Mesa, M. (2009) Terebellidae (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from the Grand Caribbean region. Zootaxa, 2320, 1 - 93." type="journal article" year="2009">Londoňo-Mesa (2009)</bibRefCitation>
that they are probably the 
<typeStatus box="[346,394,404,428]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">type</typeStatus>
specimens. The view that 
<taxonomicName box="[704,848,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="luminosus">
<emphasis box="[704,848,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. luminosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[1127,1271,405,428]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis box="[1127,1271,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[1288,1338,404,429]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">type</typeStatus>
locality, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,243,439,464]" name="Jamaica" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
) held by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartman, O." box="[352,535,439,464]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="355 - 628" refId="ref60993" refString="Hartman, O. (1959) Catalogue of the Polychaetous annelids of the world. Part 2. Sedentaria. Allan Hancock Foundation Occasional Paper, 23, 355 - 628." type="journal article" year="1959">Hartman (1959)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Holthe, T." box="[548,722,439,464]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1 - 236" refId="ref61346" refString="Holthe, T. (1986 a) Evolution, systematics, and distribution of the Polychaeta Terebellomorpha, with a catalogue of the taxa and a bibliography. Gunneria, 55, 1 - 236." type="journal article" year="1986">Holthe (1986a)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Londono-Mesa, M." box="[784,1038,439,464]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1 - 93" refId="ref62299" refString="Londono-Mesa, M. (2009) Terebellidae (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from the Grand Caribbean region. Zootaxa, 2320, 1 - 93." type="journal article" year="2009">Londoño-Mesa (2009)</bibRefCitation>
is not accepted here as differences were noted in the 
<typeStatus box="[356,415,476,500]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">types</typeStatus>
of both species including the form of the upper lip and shape of the uncini (see below for description of 
<emphasis box="[320,474,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName box="[320,466,512,536]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="purpureus">P. purpureus</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
. Possibly the view is based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Augener, H." box="[851,1052,511,536]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref59510" refString="Augener, H. (1925) Uber westindische und einige andere Polychaeten-typen von Grube (Oersted), Kroyer, Morch und Schmarda. Publicationer fra Universitets Zoologiske Museum, KObenhavn, 39, 1 - 47." type="journal article" year="1925">Augener’s (1925)</bibRefCitation>
opinion that the two species are synonymous, but Augener’s view was based on an examination of the 
<typeStatus box="[991,1050,548,572]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">types</typeStatus>
of only one of these species (
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
